Have you completed the 2020 Census? The Census determines how federal funds are spent on schools, health clinics, child nutrition programs, hospitals, fire departments, roads and highways, community development projects, and more! Your response matters because a complete and correct population count makes sure that our community gets its fair share of support for all public services.

Visit my2020census.gov or scan the QR code below to complete the 2020 Census by September 30! #UrbanaBetterTogether

post_text:
Reminder: Don't forget that we're doing meal distributions for all K-12 enrolled students! For details, please read below:

We will have meal pick up at all Elementary schools, UMS and UHS. We will also have delivery to seven mobile home communities in Urbana.

Meal distribution will be from 11:00 a.m. – 1:00 p.m. every Tuesday and Thursday. The breakfast and lunch meals picked up on Tuesday will be for Tuesday and Wednesday, and the meals picked up on Thursday will be for Thursday, Friday, and Monday. As we begin the school year, we must follow the guidelines for the National School Lunch Program.

We can only provide meals to students enrolled in Urbana schools for grades Kindergarten – 12th grade. We are also required to record your child’s/children’s name(s), grade(s), and school(s) at the time of pick up. Please email questions to usd116meals@usd116.org. #UrbanaBetterTogether

Urbana Families: Day 3 of our FAQ is now available!

To help provide staff and families with the necessary information about the upcoming school year, we have compiled a list of frequently asked questions from staff, parents, teachers, and community members regarding Urbana’s fall 2020 back to school plans at the link below. To address the most important concerns regarding our back to school plans, we’ve separated the FAQs in parts. We will be answering FAQs for the rest of the week leading up to the release of our detailed full Phase 4 back to school plan.

Today’s FAQs addresses concerns surrounding cleaning and sanitizing. If you have any questions that you feel have not been answered in this FAQ or though recent emails from The District, we encourage you to use the Phase 4 Back to School Safety Plan as a resource when it is released or please email us at contactus@usd116.org.
Today's FAQ can be viewed by clicking the link below. There, you can also download the full FAQ PDF document.

Fall 2020 Back to School Student Learning FAQ: https://usd116.org/2020faqlearning

USD116 Families: Forms for full time remote learning for fall 2020 are now available at the link below. With this link, you can access both PDF and Word documents to be downloaded and submitted via email.

In light of the COVID-19 pandemic, the District has developed a full-time remote learning option for all students. Information about the District’s full-time remote learning plan will be shared with parents/guardians on August 4, 2020 during the Board of Education Study Session and available on the District’s website shortly thereafter.

Please return this completed form to the Assistant Superintendent of Student Learning, Mrs. Kimberly Norton at knorton@usd116.org. The District will review the information submitted and contact you regarding fall instruction, or for any additional information required to process this request.

Full time remote learning forms: https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1shaorXnH9yyislrJxjjPdh8KY2jccDHO?usp=sharing

USD116 will be holding registration for "new K-12 students to the district only" on Tuesday, July 28th from 9:00 a.m. - 1:00 p.m. and Wednesday, July 29th from 2:00-5:00 p.m. at Urbana Middle School, 1201 South Vine Street.

During these days and times, the district technology team will also be available to assist returning student families with the on-line registration process.

For everyone's safety and comfort, social distancing will be practiced. Prior to entering the building, everyone will need to undergo a wellness screening. Face masks or face coverings are required for admittance.

To help with social distancing, please limit the number of family members that you bring. #UrbanaBetterTogether

post_text:
Urbana parents: Online registration for returning Urbana School District students will be unavailable on July 21 for a system update. If you have not registered your returning Urbana student, please do so as soon as possible. Families that are choosing a remote only option that is provided by USD116 should still register through the online registration process. More information will be coming in a separate document for families to indicate their preference.

Visit USD116.org/online-registration for step-by-step instructions and a video on how to register online. For assistance with logging into or using Skyward, please email onlineregistration@usd116.org. Please stay up-to-date on the registration process and Fall 2020 plans by checking your email and following us on our social media platforms.

post_text:
USD116 would like to congratulate our fabulous 2020 Young Authors winners! The Young Authors program is an event sponsored by the Illinois Language and Literacy Council, in conjunction with the Illinois Reading Council and is an optional activity for students grades K-8. Each elementary building and middle school submitted many wonderful stories! Below are the names of the 2020 winners:

Abigail Fairbanks, Urbana Middle School for The Phantom Pianist
Henri Bokata and Carter Keeley, Dr. Williams Elementary for The Survivors Story
Faris Muhammad Fauzi, King Elementary for Rufus: A Journey to Freedom
Muhammad Iftikhar, Leal Elementary for A Calamity in Venice
Austin Ogolsky, Thomas Paine Elementary for A School Day for the Books
Alice Hauser, Wiley elementary for a poem titled My Poem Home
Colton Ruud, Yankee Ridge Elementary for The Underground Temple

We look forward to following these up and coming new writers! Congratulations again on a job well done! #UrbanaBetterTogether #ProudofU116

post_text:
Hey, Urbana! We are happy to announce that Urbana School District 116 will offer a remote learning summer transition education program for 5th grade students entering 6th grade in the fall of 2020. The remote learning program will take place on Google Classroom and ZOOM and offer engaging activities and useful videos to prepare you for school in the fall. Each day you will meet your future classmates in a virtual check-in and take part in a team building activity.

For more information: https://usd116.org/ums-to-offer-remote-learning-for-incoming-6th-graders/

To sign up and learn more about the summer transition sessions, visit https://sites.google.com/usd116.org/usd116ec-12/ums?authuser=0 #UrbanaBetterTogether

post_text:
USD116 Families, please read the full update below:

On Friday, April 17, Governor Pritzker extended the school closure and remote learning for the remainder of the school year. During this extended closure, USD116 will continue to provide meals for our students via the drive-up sites and deliver food to specific neighborhoods with larger populations of children. We have and will continue to collaborate with community partners to provide additional groceries, school supplies, and remote learning materials via the drive up meal sites.

Please continue to visit the Learning Links site and our website where we have provided the tools you need to continue on your remote learning journey. Please contact us at remotelearning@usd116.org if you need any assistance with the Learning Links and at ChromebookHelp@usd116.org for your technology needs. We urge all families to stay connected with their schools and by following us on social media.

Focus on taking care of one another during these challenging times and remember we are #UrbanaBetterTogether!

post_text:
MARCH 12 4:30PM UPDATE: As a school district, we are under obligation to provide a safe, healthy work learning environment for all. In light of the above recommendations from CUPHD, Urbana School District 116 has made the difficult decision to immediately cancel all travel, competitions, school assemblies, and community gatherings from Thursday, March 12 through Sunday, April 5, 2020. This decision is being made across our region for all schools.

While we are saddened for our students and families, we must be cautious and mindful to ensure student safety. At this point in time, we hope that this temporary suspension on events and activities will allow for future events, competitions, and celebrations to occur.

We urge you to stay connected with USD116 via social media and our new COVID-19 webpage. We will continue to work closely with the Champaign-Urbana Public Health District and local authorities. We appreciate your understanding and support as the health and wellness of our USD116 community is our primary focus.

post_text:
PLEASE READ IMPORTANT UPDATE: We would like to clarify that the March 12 and March 13 parent-teacher conferences will still go on, but not face-to-face. Urbana School District #116 will not be hosting FACE-TO-FACE conferences this evening or Friday amid the recent national COVID-19 concern.

USD116 staff will contact parents via phone call, written email communication, Class Dojo, Remind app, and Bloomz. We have been advised to provide options in lieu of traditional face-to-face conferences to limit crowd numbers to under 50. For any appointments previously scheduled, teachers will contact you directly through one of the above listed methods.

All families have received this message via email and we will continue to reach out via as many platforms as possible to keep you all updated as we receive more information.

Find out more by clicking the following link: www.walktoschool.org

post_text: Today, some UHS students were treated to a congratulatory breakfast for achieving Commended status on the PSAT/NMSQT, which means they scored in the top 50k of 1.6 million students. Pictured here are UHS students Max Ando, Malcom Forsyth, Michael Tessene with National Merit semifinalist Olivia Rosenstein. Not pictured, but still recognized, are students Samuel Hummel, Luca Manton, and Megan Paluska. Congratulations students! #ProudofU116

post_text:
Here's a major Monday shoutout to Urbana Cross Country who started the year off strong! Read more about their victory below and follow the team on Twitter (@UHSXC)! #UrbanaBetterTogether #ProudofU116

The UHS girls' team finished second in their invite this weekend, and the boys finished first, making it their first invite victory in over a decade!

Olivia Rosenstein took home the individual victory on the girls' side, beating the next best runner by more than 45 seconds. Runners Celia Barbieri, Ashley Gilbert, and Sofie Skottene all blew their previous performances out of the water!

Sam Lambert led the boys to the team win, and Park Mitchell had the best improvement over last year, dropping over a minute off his time to finish 10th behind senior Jeremie Bokata.

Hey, Urbana! In the first video for this year's #UrbanaBetterTogether series, we are featuring The Urbana Free Library. Executive Director Celeste Choate talked to us about how The Urbana Free Library is helping USD116 teachers and students succeed, all of the unique things the library has to offer, and what she thinks makes Urbana the place to be!

Share with your family and friends to let them know just how great Urbana is! Watch out for our next #UrbanaBetterTogether video coming later this month.
